{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531198"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:12:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:12:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14586"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14586"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.53,0.04,0.33,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7279"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112532"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7279","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7279"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14586"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94566"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2774"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4854"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11691"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17775"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19006"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38079"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43542"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46199"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49545"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112532"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 87-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her daughter reporting increasing difficulty reading and doing crossword puzzles over the past year. She reports feeling frustrated and has stopped reading her favourite books. She has become increasingly withdrawn and spends most of her time watching television. She has a medical history of hypertension, osteoarthritis, osteoporosis, atrial fibrillation, and gastro-oesophageal reflux disease. Her medications include apixaban, metoprolol, amlodipine, pantoprazole, paracetamol, cholecalciferol, and calcium carbonate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her distance vision is 6/9 bilaterally with her current glasses, but she struggles to read standard-sized text at 40 cm. Her last eye examination was five years ago. Examination of her eyes reveals normal anterior segments and fundoscopy shows mild age-related macular changes.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recommend audio books","Evaluate appropriateness of corrective lenses","Commence antidepressant therapy","Arrange ophthalmology referral","Arrange occupational therapy assessment"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of uncorrected presbyopia, which is affecting her ability to perform near vision tasks and impacting her quality of life. The examination findings show preserved distance vision but difficulty with near vision, which is typical of presbyopia. Her withdrawal from previously enjoyed activities and lowered mood are likely secondary to her visual impairment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate initial step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eevaluate appropriateness of corrective lenses\u003C/strong\u003E as it directly addresses the underlying problem. Presbyopia is a normal age-related change in near vision that can be easily corrected with appropriate reading glasses. This simple intervention could quickly restore her ability to read and do crosswords, potentially improving her mood, social engagement and quality of life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence antidepressant therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature without first addressing the underlying cause of her mood changes. Her symptoms appear to be reactive to her functional limitation rather than primary depression. There is a well understood overlay between mood disorder and visual impairment, and her mental state should be examined after the reading glasses have been provided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange ophthalmology referral\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary as the first step for uncomplicated presbyopia. While she has mild age-related macular changes, her good distance vision suggests these are not significantly affecting her vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange occupational therapy assessment\u003C/strong\u003E may be unnecessary for someone whose primary issue appears to be uncorrected presbyopia. This might be considered if she continues to have functional difficulties after vision correction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommend audio books\u003C/strong\u003E represents an adaptation to vision loss rather than addressing the correctable underlying problem. While audio books can be useful for those with permanent vision loss, this patient\u0027s near vision impairment appears correctable with appropriate glasses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Near vision impairment in older adults is commonly due to presbyopia and is easily correctable with reading glasses.","Vision impairment can significantly impact quality of life and contribute to depression in older adults.","A thorough medication review is essential as some medications can affect vision and mood in older adults."],"references":["Whitson HE, Cronin-Golomb A, Cruickshanks KJ, et al. American Geriatrics Society and National Institute on Aging Bench-to-Bedside Conference: Sensory Impairment and Cognitive Decline in Older Adults. J Am Geriatr Soc. 2018;66(11):2052-2058. doi:10.1111/jgs.15506. Available online at ; https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6410371/","Parravano M, Petri D, Maurutto E, Lucenteforte E, Menchini F, Lanzetta P, Varano M, Van Nispen RM, Virgili G. Association between visual impairment and depression in patients attending eye clinics: a meta-analysis. JAMA ophthalmology. 2021 Jul 1;139(7):753-61. Available online at ; https://jamanetwork.com/journals/jamaophthalmology/article-abstract/2780413"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94566"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14586"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94566"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-02T13:18:30+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-02T13:20:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7279"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112532"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"S